This article is an executive order issued by President Joseph R. Biden Jr. It delegates certain functions concerning the appointment, promotion, separation, and retirement of commissioned officers of the United States Coast Guard to the Secretary of Homeland Security. The Secretary is directed to perform these functions without approval, ratification, or other action by the President. The order also grants the Secretary the authority to suspend the operation of certain laws relating to the selection, promotion, or involuntary separation of officers of the Coast Guard during times of war or national emergency. The order specifies that the delegated authority may not be exercised during a national emergency declared by the President unless specifically directed by the President. It also states that actions taken under this authority must be accounted for as required by the National Emergencies Act. The order clarifies that previous actions taken by the President regarding these matters will remain in effect unless amended, modified, or revoked pursuant to the authority conferred by this order. It defines the terms "functions" and "perform" and includes general provisions stating that the order does not affect the authority granted by law to executive departments or agencies, and it must be implemented consistent with applicable law and subject to appropriations. The order does not create any rights or benefits enforceable against the United States or any other party.